-- ── Harvester ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source hyperconverged infrastructure platform built on Kubernetes, KubeVirt and Longhorn for running VMs and containers on bare metal without licensing fees.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source, free with optional paid enterprise support$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Nuremberg, Germany$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Harvester Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Harvester is an open-source hyperconverged infrastructure platform built on Kubernetes. See its features, licensing, pros, cons and alternatives for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Harvester is an open-source hyperconverged infrastructure (HCI) platform that lets organizations run both virtual machines and containerized workloads on bare metal servers using entirely open-source components, positioning itself as a free alternative to proprietary HCI and virtualization stacks like VMware vSphere and Nutanix. Rather than building a new hypervisor from scratch, Harvester is assembled from proven cloud-native building blocks: Kubernetes for orchestration, KubeVirt for running full virtual machines as Kubernetes-native resources, Longhorn for distributed block storage, and Linux with KVM underneath for the actual virtualization layer. The result is a single installable appliance that gives operators a VMware-like experience, complete with a web UI for managing VMs, networks and storage, while everything underneath is standard open-source infrastructure with no proprietary kernel or licensing lock-in. Harvester was announced by SUSE's Rancher engineering team in 2020, shortly after SUSE completed its acquisition of Rancher Labs in December of that year. Rancher Labs had built its reputation on Rancher, a widely used open-source Kubernetes cluster management platform, and Harvester extended that lineage downward into the infrastructure layer itself: instead of assuming customers already had virtualized infrastructure to deploy Kubernetes onto, Harvester lets them build that infrastructure layer directly on bare metal using the same cloud-native tooling philosophy. Because it originated inside SUSE (and before that, Rancher Labs, headquartered in Cupertino, California before the acquisition), Harvester today is stewarded by SUSE's Rancher business unit, with SUSE itself operating out of Nuremberg, Germany as its primary operational headquarters. The project is fully open source, hosted on GitHub under an Apache 2.0-style open governance model, with active contributions from SUSE engineers and the broader community, and it integrates tightly with Rancher for multi-cluster Kubernetes management, letting administrators provision downstream Kubernetes clusters directly from VMs running inside Harvester. Technically, Harvester requires no prior Kubernetes knowledge to operate: administrators install it directly onto bare metal servers via an ISO-based installer, after which it presents a management dashboard for creating and migrating VMs, configuring networking (including VLANs and multiple network interfaces), and managing distributed storage pools backed by Longhorn, which replicates VM disk data across nodes for resilience without requiring a separate SAN or NAS appliance. Because VMs run as KubeVirt-managed pods under the hood, the same cluster can simultaneously host traditional virtualized workloads (Windows or Linux VMs migrated from legacy hypervisors) and native containerized applications, making Harvester a practical bridge for organizations modernizing legacy virtual machine estates toward Kubernetes without a disruptive, all-at-once migration. Typical deployment scenarios include data center consolidation projects replacing end-of-life or cost-prohibitive VMware licenses, edge computing sites that need a lightweight, self-contained HCI stack on a small number of physical nodes, and platform teams that want a single infrastructure layer capable of running both legacy VM-based applications and new cloud-native services. Because Harvester is completely open source with no per-CPU or per-socket licensing fees, the cost model is fundamentally different from commercial HCI: there is no purchase price, subscription or seat fee for the software itself, and organizations only pay for the bare-metal hardware they run it on plus, optionally, commercial support. SUSE offers paid consulting, migration assistance and enterprise support contracts (often bundled with SUSE's broader Rancher and virtualization offerings) for organizations that want SLA-backed assistance rather than relying on community Slack and GitHub issue support, but there is no requirement to purchase anything to deploy and run Harvester in production. Harvester's target audience is infrastructure and platform engineering teams at organizations looking to escape rising VMware and Broadcom licensing costs following Broadcom's 2023 acquisition of VMware, as well as teams already invested in the Rancher and Kubernetes ecosystem who want a unified way to manage both VMs and containers. Its most direct competitors are OpenShift Virtualization (Red Hat's KubeVirt-based offering), Proxmox VE, and commercial HCI vendors like Nutanix and VMware vSphere/vSAN; Harvester differentiates primarily on being 100 percent open source with zero licensing cost, deep native integration with Rancher for multi-cluster management, and a design philosophy built entirely from existing, battle-tested cloud-native components rather than a proprietary hypervisor.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a9e58a83-376b-4e93-b8f6-d707024da382';

