-- ── HashiCorp Vault ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Identity-based secrets management platform for securely storing, generating and tightly controlling access to tokens, passwords, certificates and encryption keys.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source, plus usage-based cloud and enterprise subscription tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (open source)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2012, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$2,000+ employees (part of IBM)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$HashiCorp Vault Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$HashiCorp Vault is a secrets management and data protection platform. See its features, pricing tiers, pros, cons and alternatives for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$HashiCorp Vault is a centralized secrets management and data protection platform that lets organizations secure, store and tightly control access to tokens, passwords, API keys, certificates and encryption keys through a unified UI, command-line interface or HTTP API. Vault addresses a problem that grows more dangerous as infrastructure scales: sensitive credentials scattered across configuration files, environment variables, source code and spreadsheets create a sprawling attack surface, and Vault's answer is to centralize those secrets behind strong authentication, fine-grained access policies, and comprehensive audit logging so every request for a secret is authenticated, authorized and recorded. Vault was built by HashiCorp, the infrastructure software company founded in 2012 in San Francisco by Mitchell Hashimoto and Armon Dadgar, as part of a broader suite of infrastructure tools that also includes Terraform for provisioning, Consul for service networking, and Nomad for workload orchestration; Vault itself was first released in 2015 and quickly became one of the most widely adopted secrets management tools in the DevOps and platform engineering world, particularly for organizations running Kubernetes and multi-cloud infrastructure. HashiCorp went public on Nasdaq in December 2021 and was subsequently acquired by IBM in a deal valued at approximately 6.4 billion dollars, a transaction that closed in February 2025; Vault, like the rest of the HashiCorp portfolio, is now part of IBM's security and infrastructure offerings while continuing under the HashiCorp brand. In August 2023, HashiCorp changed the license on its core products, including Vault, from the open-source Mozilla Public License 2.0 to the Business Source License 1.1, a move that keeps source code visible and free for internal use but restricts third parties from offering Vault as a directly competing managed service, a decision that was controversial within parts of the open-source community and prompted forks of the last MPL-licensed codebase. Technically, Vault is organized around pluggable secrets engines, each handling a different category of secret: the Key-Value engine stores arbitrary static secrets, database secrets engines generate short-lived, dynamically created database credentials on demand and automatically revoke them after a lease expires, the PKI engine issues and manages short-lived TLS certificates, and the Transit engine provides encryption as a service, letting applications encrypt and decrypt data without ever handling the raw encryption keys themselves, keeping cryptographic material entirely inside Vault. Access is controlled through Vault's policy language, evaluated against the identity of the requester, which can be authenticated via numerous methods, including cloud IAM roles (AWS, Azure, GCP), Kubernetes service accounts, LDAP, GitHub, and username and password, and every secret access is written to an immutable audit log for compliance and forensics. Dynamic secrets are one of Vault's most distinctive capabilities: instead of a database password that is created once and rotated manually (or never), Vault can generate a brand-new, unique database credential for each application or session on demand, with an automatic time-to-live after which the credential is revoked, dramatically shrinking the window in which a leaked credential remains useful to an attacker. Vault is distributed in three main forms. The Community Edition is entirely free and open source, self-hosted on the customer's own infrastructure with no secret-count limits, core secrets management, dynamic secrets, the Transit encryption engine, and identity-based access control included at no charge, though after the 2023 license change it operates under the BSL 1.1 rather than a traditional OSI-approved open-source license. HCP Vault Dedicated is HashiCorp's fully managed SaaS offering on HashiCorp Cloud Platform, with a low-cost Development tier around 0.03 dollars per hour (roughly 22 dollars per month) for non-production testing with no per-client fee, an Essentials tier for production workloads with a 99.9 percent uptime SLA starting around 1,152 dollars per month for a small cluster plus roughly 72.92 dollars per authenticated client per month, and a Standard tier adding performance replication, Sentinel policy-as-code and premium support at a higher hourly rate; a separately sold HCP Vault Secrets SaaS product was discontinued in 2025, consolidating HashiCorp's cloud secrets offering around HCP Vault Dedicated. Vault Enterprise is a self-managed license deployed on the customer's own infrastructure for organizations wanting full control over topology, storage backend and network configuration, adding the Transform secrets engine for format-preserving tokenization of sensitive data, disaster recovery replication, Sentinel governance policies and namespaces for multi-tenancy; HashiCorp does not publish Enterprise pricing, and industry sources report quotes commonly starting in the low six figures annually even for relatively small deployments. Vault's target audience is DevOps, platform engineering and security teams at organizations of any size that need to eliminate hardcoded credentials and centralize secret sprawl, ranging from startups adopting the free Community Edition to regulated enterprises in finance and healthcare requiring Vault Enterprise's compliance and governance features. Its main competitors include AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault and Google Secret Manager for cloud-native teams committed to a single provider, along with newer entrants like Infisical and Doppler that target a simpler developer experience; Vault differentiates through its cloud-agnostic design, its unusually deep dynamic secrets and encryption-as-service capabilities, and its position as the de facto standard secrets manager across the wider HashiCorp and Kubernetes ecosystem.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '7bf2641e-776f-49ba-814c-30d9468c54c8';

